    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sub Tragedy Reveals a New Russia</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Richard J Wells letter disputes August 23 editorial which criticized Russian government for slow and inadequate response to sinking of submarine Kursk</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Kursk and the Kremlin'' (editorial, Aug. 23):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Kursk and the Kremlin'' (editorial, Aug. 23):</p>
        <p>You make the case that President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia and his government were slow and inadequate in their response to the sinking of the nuclear submarine Kursk. This views the situation through Western eyes.</p>
        <p>But there is another message. Who could have imagined just a dozen years ago that Soviet citizens would even have been informed about an event involving national defense and national pride, much less that they would fearlessly and publicly respond with vigorous, even bitter, complaints about their government and its leaders?</p>
        <p>The sinking of the Kursk illuminates the path that Russia has traveled in half a generation, as well as how far it has yet to go.</p>
        <p>RICHARD J. WELLS  Chappaqua, N.Y., Aug. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
